Source: Xinhuanet, 7 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-11/07/content_3742579.htm>


Bird flu-hit county in Liaoning culls 6 million poultry
-----------------------------------------------
6 million poultry have been culled in the bird flu-hit county of
Heishan, in northeast China's Liaoning Province, local government
said on Sunday [6 Nov 2005].

The culling lasted from Saturday [5 Nov 2005] evening to Sunday noon,
with all poultry slaughtered within a radius of 3 km from the
epidemic site, said Wang Yunwen, deputy secretary-general of the
Jinzhou municipal government. Local farmers actively cooperated with
the government, he said. The farmers were being compensated for the
culling. The county allocated 9.6 million yuan (USD 1.16 million) to
the townships on Sunday, he added.

Niu Dun, vice minister of agriculture, arrived at the county with 11
experts. 3 experts gave lectures on bird flu prevention to about 150
grassroots officials on Sunday [6 Nov 2005].

Local publicity department is also producing CDs of the lectures and
publishing booklets on bird flu prevention for distribution among the
people living in the affected areas.

Local farmers found some chickens dying in Badaohao township and
reported them to the local government. China's Ministry of
Agriculture confirmed the case as H5N1 bird flu on Thursday [3 Nov
2005].

Heishan county is located on the migratory birds' route from East
Asia to Australia, and more than 20 magpies and other wild birds have
been spotted.

--
